article.description:
The Sacramento Monarchs used a second-half
surge to roll past the last-place San Antonio Silver Stars and stay in the playoff race.
article.headline: Griffith nets 11 of 17 in second half
article.linkText: Griffith's queenly effort keeps Monarchs in hunt
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- The Sacramento Monarchs used a second-half
surge to roll past the last-place San Antonio Silver Stars and stay
in the playoff race.

Yolanda Griffith had 17 points, including 11 in the second half,
to lead the Monarchs to an 80-70 victory over San Antonio on
Saturday night.

Sacramento (15-13) is in fourth place in the Western Conference,
six games behind league-leading Los Angeles with six games left in
the season. The top four teams in each conference advance to the
playoffs.

The Monarchs barely beat the Silver Stars on Thursday, 66-64.

"We needed this win," Griffith said. "At the half we talked
about things we needed to work on. We took them out of the flow of
offense and we started to hit our shots."

Edna Campbell added 15 points for the Monarchs, making 3-of-4
from 3-point range. Ticha Penicheiro had 13 points, nine assists
and five steals.

Adrienne Goodson, LaToya Thomas and Margo Dydek each scored 12
points for the Silver Stars (6-23), who set a franchise record with
their ninth straight losses.

Shannon Johnson, recognized before the game for her Olympic
gold-medal efforts, had nine points and nine assists.

Down by six, the Monarchs went on an 18-5 run, capped by
Rebekkah Brunson's layup, to take a 58-51 lead with 12 minutes
left. Campbell had seven points in the run.

"We let Campbell get started. I think they kind of took the
wind our of our sail a little bit," said Silver Stars coach Shell
Dailey. "Defensively we took some chances, too. We didn't play as
solidly as we did in the first half."

Thomas hit a 15-foot jumper with 6:42 seconds left to cut the
lead to 65-59, but that was the closest San Antonio would get.

Dydek, whose 12 points all came in the first half, helped the
Silver Stars to a 40-35 halftime lead.

The Monarchs shot 49 percent, and 6-for-10 from 3-point range.
The Silver Star had a season-high 25 turnovers, which led to 24
points.
